06740nam a22008055i 9781529220094DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a2022367371  a97815292200947 a10.56687/97815292200942doi  a(DE-B1597)645791  a(OCoLC)1340643979  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST00aHD5857b.F32 2022 4aHD5857 7aBUS0380002bisacsh04a331.2572922300aFaces of Precarity :bCritical Perspectives on Work, Subjectivities and Struggles /ced. by Joseph Choonara, Annalisa Murgia, Renato Miguel Carmo. 1aBristol : bBristol University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b8 Black and White  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIntroduction: Critical Perspectives on Precarity and Precariousness -- tConceptualizations, Subjectivities and Etymologies -- tPrécarité and Precarity: The Amazing Transnational Journey of Two Notions Unable to Form a Proper Concept in English -- tConceptualizing Precariousness: A Subject-oriented Approach -- tThe Experience of Precariousness as Vulnerable Time -- tClass, Work and Employment -- tAbove-Below, Inside-Outside: Precarity, Underclass and Social Exclusion in Demobilized Class Societies -- tClass, Classification and Conjunctures: The Use of ‘Precarity’ in Social Research -- tThe Problem with Precarity: Precarious Employment and Labour Markets -- tThe Social Foundations of Precarious Work: The Role of Unpaid Labour in the Family -- tPrecariousness in the Platform Economy -- tA Pandemic-related Turning Point: Precarious Work, Platforms and Utopian Energies -- tExperiences, Concretizations and Struggles -- tThe Embodiment of Insecurity: How Precarious Labour Market Trajectories Affect Young Workers’ Health and Wellbeing in Catalonia (Spain) -- tPrecarity and Migration: Thai Wild Berry Pickers in Sweden -- tRevisiting the Concept of Precarious Work in Times of COVID-19 -- tPrecarious Workers and Precarity through the Lens of Social Movement Studies -- tOrganizing and Self-organized Precarious Workers: The Experience of Britain -- tAfterword: A Pandemic of Precarity -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe words ‘precarity’ and ‘precariousness’ are widely used when discussing work, social conditions and experiences. However, there is no consensus on their meaning or how best to use them to explore social changes. This book shows how scholars have mapped out these notions, offering substantive analyses of issues such as the relationships between precariousness, debt, migration, health and workers’ mobilizations, and how these relationships have changed in the context of COVID-19. Bringing together an international group of authors from diverse fields, this book offers a distinctive critical perspective on the processes of precarization, focusing in particular on the European context. The Introduction, Chapters 3 and 8, and the Afterword are available Open Access via OAPEN under CC-BY-NC-ND licence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrecarious employment. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh1 aArmano, Emiliana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarata, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbier, Jean-Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelvis, Francesc X., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolíbar, Mireia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarmo, Renato Miguel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarmo, Renato Miguel, eeditor.4edt4